---
import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro';
const base = import.meta.env.BASE_URL;
---

<Layout title="What Flock Really Is">
  <div class="content">
    <span class="card-tag" style="background: rgba(230, 57, 70, 0.2); color: #E63946;">Learn &middot; 01</span>
    <h1>It's Not Just a Plate Reader</h1>
    <p class="subtitle" style="color: var(--color-muted); font-size: 1.15rem;">
      Local officials describe Flock as a camera that reads license plates, "just letters and numbers, no personal information." That is not what the company sells.
    </p>

    <h2>Vehicle Fingerprint</h2>
    <p>
      Flock's own marketing names the feature: <strong>Vehicle Fingerprint</strong>. Its cameras use AI to build a profile of each vehicle that goes far past the plate, cataloguing the make, body type, color, damage, and distinguishing features of cars, trucks, buses, and even bicycles.
    </p>
    <p>
      The profiles are granular enough to note aftermarket wheels, roof racks, and bumper stickers. The stated purpose is to track a specific vehicle <strong>even when the plate isn't visible</strong>. "Just letters and numbers" describes a product Flock doesn't actually sell.
    </p>
    <p class="source">
      Sources: Flock Safety product pages (flocksafety.com); BGR, "Flock Cameras Are Tracking More Than License Plates" (June 2026); Berkeleyside, "What are Flock cameras" (Nov 2025).
    </p>

    <h2>Searching For People, Not Just Cars</h2>
    <p>
      Flock has added AI that lets law enforcement search camera footage with plain-language descriptions of people. The ACLU documents the system surfacing results for queries like a person in a <strong>"camo hat, forest green sweater."</strong>
    </p>
    <p>
      The "we don't use facial recognition" defense misses the point. You don't need a face when the system can be searched for a hat, a beard, a tattoo, or what someone's shirt says. The cameras capture pedestrians and vehicle occupants, not only plates.
    </p>
    <p class="source">
      Source: ACLU, "Flock's Aggressive Expansions Go Far Beyond Simple Driver Surveillance" (Aug 2025).
    </p>

    <h2>Flock Nova: The Dossier Layer</h2>
    <p>
      Flock's flagship platform, <strong>Nova</strong>, fuses camera data with other databases: jail records, dispatch logs, public records, and open-source intelligence. It builds a searchable file on a person, with no warrant required. The original version even pulled in data from breaches until reporting forced the company to drop that piece.
    </p>
    <p>
      The Electronic Frontier Foundation described Nova as a <strong>"dystopian panopticon."</strong> It turns a roadside plate camera into the front end of a personal-intelligence system.
    </p>
    <p class="source">
      Sources: EFF (2025); BGR (June 2026); Flock Safety Nova product materials.
    </p>

    <h2>The Ring Doorbell Partnership: Announced, Then Beaten Back</h2>
    <p>
      In <strong>October 2025</strong>, Amazon's Ring announced a partnership with Flock. Agencies on the Nova platform would have been able to request footage from Ring doorbell cameras, an estimated <strong>10 million-plus</strong> in American homes, through a single portal. It would have bridged the largest residential camera network in the country with a license-plate surveillance company.
    </p>
    <p>
      Then people pushed back. After a Ring Super Bowl ad in February 2026 drew a wave of public backlash over surveillance, <strong>Ring and Flock canceled the integration on February 12, 2026.</strong> Both companies confirmed it never launched and no Ring footage was ever sent to Flock.
    </p>
    <p>
      Keep both halves of that. The cancellation is real, and it matters: <strong>organized public pressure killed a surveillance partnership between two of the biggest names in the business.</strong> That's the proof this work isn't futile. It's also a tactical retreat, not a structural change, the architecture that made the link possible is still there, and the companies never cited the backlash in their official reason.
    </p>
    <p class="source">
      Sources: CNN, Engadget, AP, GeekWire (Feb 12&ndash;13, 2026); Flock Safety and Ring official statements; TechCrunch (Oct 2025).
    </p>

    <h2>Connects To Predictive Policing</h2>
    <p>
      Flock's network can integrate directly into predictive-policing platforms, <strong>including Palantir</strong>. That is the bridge from a local camera to the national targeting architecture. We trace that whole chain on the next page.
    </p>

    <div class="cta-banner">
      <h3>Next: Where This Data Actually Goes</h3>
      <p>The camera is real. The abuse is documented, and a lot of it happened right here in Arizona.</p>
      <a href={`${base}network/`} class="btn">The Network &amp; The Abuse</a>
    </div>
  </div>
</Layout>
